Common prefixes: be-, er-, ge-, ver-.

The nominative is used when the noun is the subject of the sentence, i.e. the 'agent' of what is happening ('Who is doing the action?') |
*Der Mann* liest. |

When the noun is the direct object, i.e. the 'receiver' of the action in the sentence, German normally uses the accusative ('Who or what is affected by the action?') |

Der Mann liest *einen Roman*. |

In addition to the direct object, many verbs can take a second object, the indirect object ('To whom/what, or for whom/what is the action done?') |

Der Mann gibt *der Frau* einen Roman. |
